-- Abertis, EDF, Fiat, Iberdrola, Julius Baer, TomTom: Europe Equity Preview
-- Stephanie Borise
-- 2010-07-20T21:48:00Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-07-20/abertis-edf-fiat-iberdrola-julius-baer-tomtom-europe-equity-preview.html

          
          
             The following companies’ shares may
have unusual moves in  European  trading. Stock symbols are in
parentheses and prices are from the last close.  
 The  Stoxx Europe 600 Index  rose 0.1 percent to 246.35. The
 Stoxx 50 Index  gained 0.3 percent to 2,395.02. The  Euro Stoxx 50
Index , a benchmark for nations using the euro, fell 0.3 percent
to 2,627.28.  
 Abertis Infraestructuras SA  (ABE SM): The toll-road
operator’s two main shareholders and CVC Capital Partners Ltd.
extended a deadline by two weeks for banks to commit to 5.3
billion euros ($6.8 billion) of loans to acquire the company,
according to people with knowledge of the plans. The shares fell
0.1 percent to 13.84 euros.  
 Accor SA  (AC FP): Europe’s largest hotel company said
first-half revenue rose 6 percent to 2.85 billion euros as
occupancy improved. The shares added 0.8 percent to 23.19 euros.  
 Electricite de France SA  (EDF FP): Europe’s biggest
electricity generator plans to place half the French power grid
into a fund to help pay for the dismantling of nuclear reactors,
according to a person familiar with the project. The shares rose
0.5 percent to 30.63 euros.  
 Fiat SpA  (F IM): Italy’s largest carmaker plans to release
second-quarter results before the market opens. The stock fell
2.1 percent to 9.06 euros.  
 GlaxoSmithKline Plc  (GSK LN): The U.K.’s biggest drugmaker
agreed to pay more than $1 billion to resolve more than 800
cases alleging its Paxil antidepressant caused birth defects,
according to people familiar with the situation. The shares
slipped 1.2 percent, to close at 1,173.5 pence.  
 Iberdrola Renovables SA  (IBR SM): The world’s largest owner
of wind parks said first-half profit rose 6.5 percent as it
generated more electricity after completing projects. The shares
were unchanged at 2.71 euros.  
 Julius Baer Group Ltd.  (BAER VX): The Swiss private bank
reports half-year earnings. The stock fell 0.8 percent to 32.01
francs.  
 Portugal Telecom SGPS SA  (PTC PL): Portugal’s largest phone
company is in discussions to buy part of Tele Norte Leste
Participacoes SA, said a person with knowledge of the matter.
Such a deal may allow Portugal Telecom to sell its stake in its
existing Brazilian venture, Brasilcel NV, to Telefonica SA (TEF
SM), the person said. PT shares gained 1.8 percent to 8.16
euros.  
 Safilo Group SpA  (SFL IM): the world’s second-largest maker
of eyewear was raised to “buy” from “sell” at UniCredit. The
stock climbed 0.4 percent to 8.01 euros.  
 TomTom NV  (TOM2 NA): Europe’s biggest maker of portable
navigation devices may report second-quarter profit of 26
million euros, according to the average of 6 analyst estimates
compiled by Bloomberg. TomTom rose 0.2 percent to 4.81 euros.  
 Valeo SA  (FR FP): Shareholder Pardus Capital Management LP
cut its voting stake in the auto-parts supplier to 9.72 percent,
the French stock market regulator said. The shares fell 1.7
percent to 22.94 euros.  
 Vivendi SA  (VIV FP): The world’s largest video-games
supplier and music company asked banks for a 1 billion-euro
credit line to refinance existing debt, according to two people
involved in the discussions. The shares declined 0.9 percent to
17.05 euros.  
